### Constructors in C#

A constructor is a special method that initializes an object when it is created. It has the same name as the class and no return type.

### Default Constructor

Every class has an implicit parameterless constructor if no constructors are defined:

```csharp
public class Person
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }
    // Implicit default constructor: Person() { }
}
```

### Custom Constructors

```csharp
public class Person
{
    public string Name { get; }
    public int Age { get; }

    // Parameterized constructor
    public Person(string name, int age)
    {
        Name = name;
        Age = age;
    }
}
```

### Constructor Overloading

```csharp
public class Rectangle
{
    public int Width { get; }
    public int Height { get; }

    public Rectangle() : this(1, 1) { }  // Default
    public Rectangle(int side) : this(side, side) { }  // Square
    public Rectangle(int width, int height)
    {
        Width = width;
        Height = height;
    }
}
```

### Constructor Chaining with : this()

```csharp
public class Employee
{
    public string Name { get; }
    public int Id { get; }
    public string Department { get; }

    public Employee(string name) : this(name, 0) { }
    public Employee(string name, int id) : this(name, id, "General") { }
    public Employee(string name, int id, string department)
    {
        Name = name;
        Id = id;
        Department = department;
    }
}
```

### Static Constructors

Runs once before any instance is created:

```csharp
public class Database
{
    public static readonly string ConnectionString;

    static Database()
    {
        ConnectionString = "Server=localhost;Database=MyDB;";
        Console.WriteLine("Static constructor called");
    }
}
```

### Primary Constructors (C# 12+)

```csharp
public class Person(string name, int age)
{
    public string Name { get; } = name;
    public int Age { get; } = age;
}
```

### Private Constructors

Prevents instantiation from outside:

```csharp
public class Logger
{
    private Logger() { }
    public static Logger Instance { get; } = new Logger();
}
```

> **Key Point:** If you define any constructor, the default parameterless constructor is no longer generated. Use `: this()` to chain constructors and avoid code duplication. Static constructors run once per type and cannot have parameters.

### Constructor Rules

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Name | Must match class name |
| Return type | No return type (not even void) |
| Overloading | Can have multiple constructors |
| Inheritance | Base constructor called with `: base()` |

